            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Mei-Lin Connolly is a product of two San Franciscos. Her father, a third-generation Irish-American history teacher with a love for city lore, and her mother, a pragmatic software engineer who immigrated from Shanghai in the 1990s, raised her in a foggy Sunset District home filled with books and server racks. This household of dueling intellectual traditions\u2014humanistic storytelling and data-driven logic\u2014shaped Mei-Lin\u2019s worldview from an early age. She learned to see the city not just through its history but through its patterns.\n\nHer educational journey mirrored this dual upbringing. After graduating from Lowell High School, she attended UC Berkeley, initially drawn to sociology. However, a pivotal class on urban displacement showed her the power of raw data to either obscure or illuminate human struggle. She realized that the most compelling stories were backed by undeniable evidence. This revelation led her to pursue a graduate degree in Information Management and Systems, where she honed the skills to find the narrative hidden within spreadsheets and databases.\n\nNow, as a data journalist for a prominent online publication, Mei-Lin\u2019s work is her calling. She spends her days transforming complex datasets on housing, transit, and income inequality into accessible, evocative visualizations and articles. Her turning point as a professional came last year, when her investigation into the disparate impact of Muni route changes on low-income communities led to a reversal of policy by the SFMTA.\n\nMei-Lin lives in a rent-controlled one-bedroom apartment in NOPA, a neighborhood she loves for its proximity to both Golden Gate Park and the lively Divisadero corridor. Her 1.8-mile commute on the 21-Hayes bus is a daily ritual of observation, a moment to unplug from screens and watch the city\u2019s diverse population coexist. She has a close-knit circle of friends, a mix of fellow SF natives and grad school peers, and a steady relationship with a landscape architect named Ben.\n\nHer aspirations are clear: she dreams of leading a multi-year, grant-funded project mapping the generational flow of wealth and displacement in the Bay Area. For Mei-Lin, San Francisco is more than just a home; it is the central character in the story she feels compelled to tell, one line of code and one human insight at a time."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nShe was ten. Her father spread faded photos of the Sunset\u2019s rolling sand dunes on the floor. \u201cThis was all sand, Mei,\u201d he\u2019d said, his voice full of wonder. Later, her mother showed her a digitized city map, the perfect grid of the avenues a testament to logic. In that moment, staring at the screen, Mei-Lin didn\u2019t see a contradiction. She saw the ghost of the dunes inside the grid. It was the first time she understood that data was just another way to tell a story about a place.\n\n2.\nIt was in a stuffy lecture hall her junior year at Berkeley. The professor projected a spreadsheet mapping the 1960s \"redevelopment\" of the Fillmore. Next to columns of addresses and acquisition dates, he showed photos of the thriving Black-owned businesses that were simply erased. For Mei-Lin, the numbers suddenly had a heartbeat, a sound, a soul. It was no longer theory; it was an excavation of injustice. She changed her entire academic path that week, convinced that data held the ghosts, and it was her job to make them speak.\n\n3.\nAfter her Muni investigation was published, she took the 21-Hayes to work. An elderly woman with a grocery cart got on, chatting with the driver about the route being restored. \u201cA real lifesaver for my knees,\u201d the woman said. Mei-Lin ducked her head, a hot, sharp pride stinging her eyes. It wasn\u2019t about the article\u2019s pageviews or the praise from her editor. It was this. The quiet, tangible proof that her work had bent the world back toward fairness, even just a little, for one person on her bus.\n\n4.\nWalking with Ben through Golden Gate Park on a rare sunny Saturday, he explained how a path was designed to obscure and then reveal a view of Stow Lake. He saw soil and sightlines; she saw the demographic data of the park\u2019s visitors, a complex pattern of access and leisure. He touched the leaf of a fern, and she imagined a data point. Looking at him trace the landscape with his hands, she felt a quiet click of understanding. They were both just trying to map the city\u2019s heart in their own language.\n\n5.\nIt was 2 a.m. in her NOPA apartment the night before her Muni story was due. The city was silent except for the low hum of her computer. Drowning in spreadsheets, she nearly gave up, the human element lost in the cells. Then she remembered her father\u2019s voice telling her about the cable car operators\u2019 strike of \u201851. She found the narrative thread again, not in the numbers, but in the imagined exhaustion of a single commuter. That moment defined her method: find the person inside the pattern, always."
